Puerto Vallarta Girls' Trip

Overview

Puerto Vallarta in early November offers warm, sunny weather and minimal rain—perfect for our six to seven-night getaway. We’ll stay in vibrant neighborhoods like the Zona Romántica or Centro so nightlife, beaches, and restaurants are just steps away. Our budget is around $1.5k per person, giving us a total lodging budget of about $6k for the trip. We prefer exploring local eateries and bars rather than all-inclusive dining, and we’d like a lively spot within walking distance of the beach and the nightlife scene.

Best Areas to Stay

Zona Romántica (Old Town)

This is the heart of Puerto Vallarta’s nightlife. Cobblestone streets are lined with bars, clubs, cafés and galleries, and Playa Los Muertos is only minutes away【2†L159-L168】. Expect busy sidewalks, live music, street performers, and a friendly, inclusive crowd. It’s safe and perfect for walking to dinner and stumbling home after a night out.

Centro & 5 de Diciembre

Just north of Old Town, these neighborhoods include the iconic Malecón boardwalk, the Guadalupe Church, and plenty of art sculptures【4†L193-L201】. Hotels here are only a few blocks from the beach and nightlife; the area is bustling but slightly less saturated with bars than the Romantic Zone.

Hotel Zone & Marina

These areas house large resorts, malls and upscale marinas. They’re quieter and more family‑oriented, and you’ll need taxis or a 20–30 minute walk to reach downtown nightlife【2†L130-L139】. We’ll avoid them since we want to be in the center of the action.

Recommended Lodging Options

Pinnacle Resorts (Signature 180 / 179)

Modern condo-style suites in a prime hillside location overlooking Los Muertos Beach. Adults‑only and just a two‑minute walk to the bars and restaurants via a funicular or stairs【12†L153-L161】.

  • Location: 2 blocks from Playa Los Muertos; steps from Olas Altas nightlife【12†L153-L161】.
  • Amenities: Rooftop infinity pool with swim‑up bar, gym, spa services, concierge, weekly maid service【12†L155-L163】.
  • Suites: One- or two‑bedroom condos with full kitchen, washer/dryer, private terrace and ocean or city views【12†L167-L175】.
  • Price: ~$250–$400 per night for a 1BR (sleeps 3); $500–$600 for 2BR (sleeps 5).
  • Pros: Luxury feel, social rooftop bar (Chic‑tini)【48†L147-L155】, unbeatable location, amazing sunset views.
  • Cons: Fills up quickly; slight uphill walk.
Book at Pinnacle Resorts

Playa Los Arcos Hotel & Suites

A Mexican‑style resort right on Playa Los Muertos in the middle of the Romantic Zone. It’s unbeatable for location and value【24†L28-L36】.

  • Location: On the sand in Zona Romántica; 1–5 minutes to bars and clubs【24†L38-L46】.
  • Amenities: Three interconnected pools with a swim‑up bar, beach palapas, nightly entertainment, optional all‑inclusive dining, spa and activities【56†L7-L10】.
  • Rooms: One‑bedroom suites with two double beds and kitchenettes or standard rooms. Traditional decor.
  • Price: ~$150–$200 per room/night; $300–$400 for two rooms.
  • Pros: Unbeatable beachfront location; optional all‑inclusive; sister adults‑only rooftop pool across the street.
  • Cons: Dated rooms; can be noisy and family‑oriented【56†L25-L29】.
Book at Playa Los Arcos

Villa Premiere Boutique Hotel (Adults‑Only)

A chic, adults‑only boutique hotel on the beach just north of the Malecón【48†L99-L105】. Perfect if you want relaxation and luxury with easy access to downtown.

  • Location: On the beach in 5 de Diciembre; 10‑minute walk to downtown【48†L99-L105】.
  • Amenities: Two pools (one infinity), swim‑up bar, beach cabanas, spa, gym, three restaurants, optional all‑inclusive【48†L98-L105】.
  • Rooms: Modern oceanfront rooms with balconies; option for Deluxe or Master suites.
  • Price: ~$300–$400 per room/night.
  • Pros: Personalized service, quiet atmosphere, welcome champagne and mini massage.
  • Cons: A longer walk (15 mins) or short taxi ride to nightlife; not a party hotel.
Book at Villa Premiere

Almar Resort & Mantamar Beach Club

An adults‑only, LGBTQ‑friendly resort on Playa Los Muertos featuring a built‑in day party scene. Ideal if you want to combine beach lounging with rooftop cocktails and live DJs.

  • Location: At the south end of Los Muertos Beach; ~8–10 minute walk to the main Zona Romántica strip.
  • Amenities: Infinity pools, jacuzzis, Mantamar Beach Club, rooftop bar “The Top”, spa, on‑site restaurants and bars【43†L1-L8】.
  • Rooms: Modern suites and 2BR units with Jacuzzis and ocean views; some timeshare categories.
  • Price: ~<$200 per standard room; ~$400 per 2‑bedroom suite.
  • Pros: Non‑stop party vibe, beach club access, great for meeting other travelers.
  • Cons: Loud atmosphere; timeshare pressures; uphill walk back.
Book at Almar Resort

Tropicana Hotel

A no‑frills, budget beachfront hotel on the south end of Playa Los Muertos. If you’d rather spend your budget on excursions and nightlife, this is a solid pick【2†L175-L183】.

  • Location: At the far south end of Playa Los Muertos; ~5–7 minute walk to Zona Romántica nightlife.
  • Amenities: Large beachfront pool with swim‑up bar, private beach area, open‑air restaurant and bar.
  • Rooms: Basic Mexican‑style decor with two double beds; many have balconies with partial ocean view.
  • Price: ~$100–$130 per room/night; $200–$250 for two rooms.
  • Pros: Cheap beachfront option; quiet at night; friendly staff.
  • Cons: Dated decor; firm beds; no elevators in some buildings.
Book at Tropicana Hotel

Airbnb & VRBO Rentals

Renting an apartment or condo can give you more space and the ability to cook and pre‑party. Here are some standout options:

  • Surf‑Inspired Boho Bungalow: Modern 2BR condo in the center of the Romantic Zone with a rooftop infinity pool, gym and recreation room【15†L401-L409】. Sleeps four with full kitchen; approx. $150/night【15†L411-L419】.
  • Sayan Beach Luxury Condos: High‑end 2BR or 4BR penthouses with private splash pools, multiple shared pools, gym and on‑site restaurant【15†L319-L327】【15†L323-L330】. Steps from the beach and a five‑minute walk to Old Town【15†L331-L339】. Prices vary ($400+ per night for 2BR).
  • Loft 268 Condos: Contemporary building 3 blocks from the nightlife strip with rooftop pool & bar and stylish interiors【16†L207-L215】. Around $200–$250 per night.

Be sure your rental is truly in the flat area of Zona Romántica (some listings labeled “Romantic Zone” are up steep hills). Always read recent reviews for noise and Wi‑Fi quality before booking.

All‑Inclusive & Package Deals

Velas Vallarta

An oceanfront all‑inclusive resort in Marina Vallarta offering a Fall 2025 package: kids stay free, discounted teen rates, suite upgrades, a $300 resort credit, golf discounts and flexible check‑in/check‑out【794206824937097†L51-L71】. Suites feature kitchenettes and balconies. Three restaurants, a swim‑up bar and daily entertainment are included.

Location: Marina Vallarta (quieter area, short taxi ride to Old Town).

Price: From ~$350 per suite/night (package deals vary by date).

Grand Velas Riviera Nayarit

A five‑star all‑inclusive resort in Nuevo Vallarta. Suites start at 1,000 sq ft with teak furnishings, Nespresso machines and private terraces【947226415594392†L73-L103】. Guests enjoy gourmet dining (French, Italian and Asian fusion), boogie boarding and kayaking, and a world‑class spa (treatments cost extra). This is a luxurious splurge for those wanting the very best.

Location: Nuevo Vallarta (about 6 miles north of downtown).

Price: From ~$600 per suite/night.

Secrets Vallarta Bay

Adults‑only resort on Banderas Bay offering the “Unlimited‑Luxury” plan: unlimited gourmet dining, top‑shelf spirits, 24‑hour room & concierge service, pool and beach waiter service, daily activities, nightly entertainment and free Wi‑Fi【781082175298333†L2416-L2572】. It has 271 ocean‑view suites with whirlpool tubs and swim‑up options. Kayak lists rooms starting around $296 per night【369553857164828†L321-L347】.

Location: Hotel Zone, 10‑minute drive from the airport and 20‑minute walk to downtown【369553857164828†L321-L347】.

Price: From ~$300 per suite/night (varies with specials).

Dreams Vallarta Bay

Family‑friendly all‑inclusive near the Malecón. Includes all onsite food & beverages, taxes and tips【543316886903366†L300-L404】. There are three pools (plus kids’ pool), five restaurants, a hydrotherapy spa, tennis courts, bike rentals and a long list of water and land sports such as kayaking, snorkeling and climbing wall【543316886903366†L300-L404】.

Location: Hotel Zone, a short ride to downtown.

Price: Around ~$300 per room/night.

Hyatt Ziva Puerto Vallarta

All‑inclusive resort located on private Las Estacas Beach. Features multiple pools, rain‑shower marble bathrooms, hydromassage tubs, a spa and a KidZ Club【984914714935980†L459-L499】. Dining spans Italian, Asian, Mexican and American cuisines, plus a 24‑hour snack bar. Activities include jungle excursions and nightly water light shows. Perfect for those wanting an upscale resort with lots to do.

Location: South of Old Town on a secluded beach.

Price: Around ~$400 per room/night.

Hilton Vallarta Riviera

An all‑inclusive resort featuring 444 suites with balconies, two infinity pools, multiple restaurants and bars, spa, fitness center and nightly entertainment【117281286821827†L433-L458】. It sits on its own beach with snorkeling and water sports. Kayak notes king rooms start around $220 per night and double rooms around $244【117281286821827†L470-L641】.

Location: South Hotel Zone, about 10 minutes from downtown.

Price: ~$220–$400 per room/night depending on category and season.

Suggested 7‑Day Itinerary

Day 1: Arrival & Sunset Drinks

Check in, unpack and relax by the pool or beach. At sunset, head to Los Muertos Pier for a spectacular view【50†L195-L203】 and toast your first night with hibiscus margaritas at Cuates y Cuetes【48†L147-L155】. Dinner can be casual street tacos before sampling a bar or two (Margarita Grill, Pinnacle’s Chic‑tini bar). Keep it low‑key to recover from travel.

Day 2: Explore Old Town & Malecón Nightlife

Have breakfast at a local café, then wander the colorful streets of Zona Romántica and browse the markets on Isla Cuale【50†L174-L182】. Spend the afternoon lounging at a beach club—Swell or Sapphire are chill options【24†L77-L83】. After dark, explore the Malecón’s sculptures and street performers【50†L195-L203】, dine at a Cuban spot with live salsa, then dance until late at Mandala, La Vaquita or Bar Morelos.

Day 3: Hike & Beach Recovery

Start with chilaquiles at Fredy’s Tucan, then hike up to the Mirador de La Cruz viewpoint for panoramic city views【50†L229-L237】. Cool off at Conchas Chinas or take a bus to Bucerías for a change of scenery【50†L253-L261】. In the evening, enjoy ceviche and margaritas at Tuna Azul【50†L266-L277】, then bar‑hop within Zona Romántica—Mr. Flamingo and La Noche are must‑visits.

Day 4: Boating Adventure

Book a boat trip. Option A: hike from Boca de Tomatlán through hidden beaches and snorkel before lunch at Las Animas【50†L284-L307】. Option B: catamaran tour to the Marietas Islands with snorkeling and open bar【50†L284-L307】. After returning, enjoy a DIY taco tour in Old Town before a quiet night in or a relaxed bar session.

Day 5: Jungle Adventure & Night Out

Get your adrenaline fix on a ziplining & rappelling tour through the Sierra Madre【45†L23-L27】 or rent ATVs to explore mountain villages. After cleaning up, treat yourself to a nice dinner (La Capella or Joe Jack’s) and, if energy remains, experience the Thursday ArtWalk or karaoke before heading to a favorite club.

Day 6: Day Trip & Rhythms of the Night

Choose between a boat trip to Yelapa for secluded beaches and waterfalls【24†L29-L37】【24†L38-L46】 or a road trip north to San Pancho and Sayulita for surfing and boho vibes. In the evening, splurge on the Rhythms of the Night dinner‑and‑show cruise【18†L31-L35】 or join a guided Vallarta Crawl for a final blowout【18†L41-L45】.

Day 7: Farewell Brunch & Departure

Savor a beachfront brunch at La Palapa or a café of your choice【24†L29-L37】, pick up any last souvenirs, and reflect on your memorable week before heading home. Extend your stay if you want more beach time!
